## 3) Plant Physiology (Photosynthesis, Respiration, Growth, Transport)

### Photosynthesis – equation and site
- Equation: 6CO2 + 12H2O → C6H12O6 + 6O2 + 6H2O.
- Site: Chloroplast; grana (light reaction); stroma (Calvin cycle). 【turn0search13】

### Light reaction
- PS II (P680) → water splitting (photolysis) releases O2.
- Electron transport → PS I (P700) → NADPH formation.
- Photophosphorylation: ATP synthesis via chemiosmosis (Z-scheme). 【turn0search13】

### Calvin cycle (C3 cycle)
- Phase 1: Carboxylation (RuBisCO fixes CO2 to RuBP → unstable 3PGA).
- Phase 2: Reduction (ATP + NADPH → G3P).
- Phase 3: Regeneration of RuBP.
- First stable product: 3-PGA (3-phosphoglycerate).
- Number of CO2 to fix 1 glucose = 6; 12 NADPH, 18 ATP needed.

### C4 vs CAM
- C4 (e.g., maize, sugarcane): Kranz anatomy; bundle sheath cells; CO2 fixed as OAA (oxaloacetate) in mesophyll → malate → bundle sheath; higher temp & light efficiency; no photorespiration.
- CAM (e.g., pineapple, opuntia): stomata open at night (CO2 fixation to malate); stored in vacuole; used in day for Calvin cycle; succulents/xerophytes.

### Respiration – glycolysis to ETS
- Glycolysis: cytoplasm; 1 glucose → 2 pyruvate; net 2 ATP + 2 NADH.
- Link reaction/pyruvate decarboxylation: mitochondrial matrix; pyruvate → acetyl-CoA + CO2 + NADH.
- Krebs cycle: matrix; 3 NADH, 1 FADH2, 1 ATP per acetyl-CoA; 2 CO2.
- ETS/Oxidative phosphorylation: inner mitochondrial membrane; O2 final acceptor; water formed; maximum ATP (about 30–32).

### Plant growth regulators (hormones)
- Auxin, Gibberellin, Cytokinin, Ethylene, Abscisic acid.
- Trick: “Aunt Gina Can Always Eat” (Auxin, Gibberellin, Cytokinin, Abscisic acid, Ethylene). 【turn1fetch0】
- Functions (quick hits):
  - Auxin: apical dominance; cell elongation; rooting (IAA, IBA).
  - Gibberellin: bolting; seed germination; rosette plant flowering.
  - Cytokinin: cell division; delay leaf senescence (anti-aging).
  - Ethylene: fruit ripening; leaf & flower abscission; triple response.
  - Abscisic acid (ABA): stress hormone; stomatal closure; seed dormancy.

### Seed dormancy and vernalization
- Dormancy: ABA and inhibitors; hard seed coat; requirements like cold/stratification.
- Vernalization: low temperature exposure for flowering (e.g., winter varieties of wheat/barley).

