## 7) Ecology and Environment

### Ecosystem components
- Abiotic: light, temperature, water, soil.
- Biotic: producers, consumers, herbivores, carnivores, decomposers.

### Energy flow
- 10% law: only ~10% energy transferred per trophic level (Lindeman).
- Pyramid of energy always upright; pyramids of number/biomass can be inverted.

### Ecological pyramids
- Pyramid of numbers; pyramid of biomass; pyramid of energy.
- Key point: inverted biomass pyramid in sea (phytoplankton low biomass, zooplankton more).

### Biogeochemical cycles
- Carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus, water cycles.
- Nitrogen fixation: Rhizobium (root nodules), Azotobacter (free-living), cyanobacteria (Anabaena); industrial (Haber); lightning.
- Denitrification: Pseudomonas, Thiobacillus.

### Population ecology
- Natality, mortality, immigration, emigration.
- Carrying capacity (K): logistic growth (S-shaped curve); exponential (J-shaped) overshoot.

### Biodiversity and conservation
- Alpha (local), beta (between habitats), gamma (regional) diversity.
- Hotspots: Western Ghats, Himalaya, Indo-Burma, Sundaland (high endemism + threat).
- In situ: national parks, sanctuaries, biosphere reserves; ex situ: zoos, botanical gardens, seed banks.

### Environmental issues
- Pollution types: air (CO, CO2, SO2, NO2, particulates); water (sewage, industrial effluents, eutrophication); soil (pesticides, fertilizers).
- Greenhouse gases: CO2, CH4, N2O, CFCs → global warming.
- Ozone depletion: CFCs release Cl; ozone layer in stratosphere; UV-B increase.

